AirAsia, Sime, Poly, Tracoma, Uzma: Malaysia Equity Preview

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-03-03T00:14:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-03/airasia-sime-poly-tracoma-uzma-malaysia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index fell 0.2 percent to
1,499.28.        AirAsia Bhd. (AIRA)  : Southeast Asia’s biggest discount
airline said it signed an agreement with Tune Money Sdn. to
provide insurance products to the carrier’s customers, according
to a company statement. AirAsia fell 6.3 percent to 2.40
ringgit.        KNM Group Bhd. (KNMG)  : The Employees Provident Fund,
Malaysia’s largest pension fund, announced net purchases of 4.2
million shares in the oil and gas services provider, a stock
exchange filing showed. KNM fell 6.4 percent to 2.34 ringgit.       Poly Glass Fibre (M) Bhd. (PGF MK): The Malaysian
manufacturer of fiber glass wool said it will spend more than 10
million ringgit ($3.3 million) to expand its plant capacity by
50 percent, according to a company statement. The shares were
unchanged at 36.5 sen.        Sime Darby Bhd. (SIME)  : The plantation, auto and
property group hasn’t signed any agreement to invest in an oil
palm plantation in Cameroon, the company said in a statement.
Sime is considering investing 7.5 billion ringgit in a 300,000
hectare (741,300 acres) palm oil plantation in Cameroon, the
Financial Times reported on Feb. 28. Sime fell 0.1 percent to
9.03 ringgit.        Tracoma Holdings Bhd. (TRAH)  : Shares of the auto-parts
maker will be de-listed on March 14 after it failed to submit a
plan to restore its finances on time, the stock exchange said in
a statement. The company can appeal, the bourse said. Tracoma
was unchanged at 6 sen.        Uzma Bhd. (UZMA)  : The oil and gas engineering services
provider said it won a 200 million-ringgit contract to provide a
low pressure system for Petroliam Nasional Bhd.’s domestic
upstream operations. The shares fell 4.5 percent to 2.13
ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
